{"parentUuid":"8391e6cb-5af7-4619-9330-e66aa6ba2e9e","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"c899109a-85f0-4ce2-8d4b-537fc48bb9f2","agentId":"af29f71b461c23f95","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_8KOIs96FclKc50U1jyuAzHqt","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The following code sections were retrieved:\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.5RigorFlowMerger/improve-task-unified-tier.md\n     1\t---\n     2\tcomponent: task-unified-tier\n     3\tdeliverable: D-0026\n     4\tsource_comparison: comparison-task-unified-tier.md\n     5\tverdict: IC stronger\n     6\tprinciple_primary: Deterministic Gates\n     7\tprinciple_secondary: Scalable Quality Enforcement\n     8\tgenerated: 2026-03-15\n     9\t---\n    10\t\n    11\t# Improvement Plan: Task-Unified Tier System\n    12\t\n    13\tTraceability source: D-0022 merged-strategy.md. All items trace to one or more of the five architectural principles.\n    14\t\n    15\t---\n    16\t\n    17\t## ITEM TU-001 — CRITICAL FAIL Conditions for Unconditional Gate Failure\n    18\t\n    19\t**Priority**: P0\n    20\t**Effort**: S\n    21\t**Classification**: strengthen existing code\n    22\t**patterns_not_mass**: true — adopting the audit-validator's CRITICAL FAIL pattern (unconditional gate failure for specific failure types) as a formalized CRITICAL condition class in the tier system, not LW's behavioral-only quality gate application\n    23\t**Why not full import**: LW's CRITICAL FAIL equivalent is applied through behavioral-only quality gate instructions without programmatic automation (explicitly rejected in D-0022 Principle 2); IC's CRITICAL condition class must be programmatically enforced, not only instructional.\n    24\t\n    25\t**File paths and change description**:\n    26\t- `src/superclaude/cli/pipeline/gates.py` — Add `CriticalFailCondition` dataclass to represent a CRITICAL FAIL trigger: `condition_type: str`, `description: str`, `always_blocks: bool = True`. Add `critical_conditions: list[CriticalFailCondition]` to `GateCriteria`. When any critical condition is matched, `gate_passed()` returns `(False, f\"CRITICAL: {condition_type}\")` regardless of all other metrics.\n    27\t- `src/superclaude/cli/pipeline/models.py` — Add `GateCriteria.critical_conditions` field with default empty list.\n    28\t- `.claude/skills/sc-task-unified-protocol/SKILL.md` — Document the CRITICAL FAIL conditions for STRICT-tier tasks: (1) Sequential or Serena MCP unavailable — unconditional FAIL (cannot degrade), (2) output file absent after max turns — unconditional FAIL, (3) classification header absent in STRICT-tier task output — unconditional FAIL.\n    29\t- `src/superclaude/skills/sc-task-unified-protocol/SKILL.md` — Sync copy.\n    30\t\n    31\t**Rationale**: D-0022 Principle 2 (Deterministic Gates), direction 2: \"Define specific failure types that force unconditional gate failure regardless of overall metrics.\" Also Principle 2: \"a STRICT-tier task that cannot reach its Sequential + Serena MCP requirements should fail (not degrade).\"\n    32\t\n    33\t**Dependencies**: None\n    34\t**Acceptance criteria**: `CriticalFailCondition` exists in gates.py; `GateCriteria` has `critical_conditions` field; a critical condition returns FAIL from `gate_passed()` regardless of other criteria; SKILL.md documents the three named CRITICAL conditions for STRICT-tier tasks.\n    35\t**Risk**: Low. Additive to gate model; existing GateCriteria without critical_conditions list behaves identically to current behavior.\n    36\t\n    37\t---\n    38\t\n    39\t## ITEM TU-002 — Output-Type-Specific Gate Application\n    40\t\n    41\t**Priority**: P1\n    42\t**Effort**: M\n    43\t**Classification**: add new code\n    44\t**patterns_not_mass**: true — adopting LW's output-type-specific gate tables (different verification for code vs. analysis vs. opinion outputs) as an output-type discriminator in IC's tier routing, not LW's behavioral-only manual quality gate application\n    45\t**Why not full import**: LW's output-type gates are applied manually by human operators selecting from a quality gate menu; IC must apply output-type discrimination programmatically through the tier routing logic. LW's specific gate tables for each output type are not adopted wholesale; the discriminator pattern is.\n...\n    50\t- `.claude/skills/sc-tasklist-protocol/rules/tier-classification.md` — Add output-type detection rules: if all affected files are `*.md` → output_type=documentation; if primary deliverable is a comparison/analysis report → output_type=analysis; if primary deliverable involves code changes → output_type=code.\n    51\t- `src/superclaude/skills/sc-tasklist-protocol/rules/tier-classification.md` — Sync copy.\n    52\t\n    53\t**Rationale**: D-0022 Principle 2 (Deterministic Gates), direction 3: \"Phase 7 should integrate output-type discrimination into the STRICT/STANDARD/LIGHT/EXEMPT routing so that documentation tasks are not subjected to code-verification overhead, and analysis tasks are not subjected to structural-linting gates.\"\n...\n    87\t\n    88\t**File paths and change description**:\n    89\t- `.claude/skills/sc-task-unified-protocol/SKILL.md` — Clarify the confidence <0.70 handling: when classification confidence is below 0.70, the task classification is BLOCKED and requires user confirmation. The blocking message must include: the computed tier, the competing tier (highest alternative), and the specific keywords causing the split. The task must not proceed until the user confirms or overrides.\n    90\t- `src/superclaude/skills/sc-task-unified-protocol/SKILL.md` — Sync copy.\n    91\t- `.claude/skills/sc-tasklist-protocol/rules/tier-classification.md` — Add explicit blocking message format for low-confidence classifications.\n    92\t\n    93\t**Rationale**: D-0022 Principle 2 (Deterministic Gates) and existing tier system design: confidence <0.70 must produce a deterministic outcome (BLOCKED, awaiting user confirmation) not a soft degradation to the computed tier.\n    94\t\n    95\t**Dependencies**: None\n    96\t**Acceptance criteria**: SKILL.md specifies that confidence <0.70 blocks execution pending user confirmation; the blocking message format includes tier, competing tier, and keywords; no code path proceeds without confirmation at <0.70 confidence.\n    97\t**Risk**: Low. Clarifying existing documented behavior; no behavioral regression for high-confidence classifications.\n...\n\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.5RigorFlowMerger/comparison-task-unified-tier.md\n...\n    20\t\n    21\t**Key strengths** (`src/superclaude/skills/sc-tasklist-protocol/rules/tier-classification.md:76`, `.claude/commands/sc/task-unified.md`):\n    22\t- Automatic classification: same task description → same tier, every time\n    23\t- STRICT > EXEMPT > LIGHT > STANDARD conflict resolution priority\n    24\t- Critical path override: `auth/`, `security/`, `crypto/` paths always CRITICAL\n    25\t- Compound phrase overrides: `\"fix security\"` → STRICT despite `\"fix\"` → STANDARD default\n    26\t- Confidence threshold: <70% triggers user confirmation before execution begins\n    27\t- `--skip-compliance` escape hatch with <12% usage target\n...\n    40\t\n    41\t### IC Evidence\n    42\t| File | Line | Claim |\n    43\t|---|---|---|\n    44\t| `.claude/skills/sc-tasklist-protocol/rules/tier-classification.md` | 76 | Tier-to-verification routing: STRICT → quality-engineer (3-5K tokens, 60s) |\n    45\t| `.claude/commands/sc/task-unified.md` | — | Classification decision tree: override → compound → keyword → context → conflict |\n    46\t| `src/superclaude/core/ORCHESTRATOR.md` | 152 | Context boosters: >2 files +0.3 STRICT; security paths +0.4 STRICT |\n    47\t| `.claude/commands/sc/task-unified.md` | — | STRICT MCP requirement: Sequential + Serena; fallback NOT allowed |\n    48\t| `.claude/commands/sc/task-unified.md` | — | Critical path override: auth/, security/, crypto/ always CRITICAL |\n...\n\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.5RigorFlowMerger/strategy-ic-task-unified.md\n...\n    22\t\n    23\t```\n    24\t<!-- SC:TASK-UNIFIED:CLASSIFICATION -->\n    25\tTIER: [STRICT|STANDARD|LIGHT|EXEMPT]\n    26\tCONFIDENCE: [0.00-1.00]\n    27\t...\n    28\t<!-- /SC:TASK-UNIFIED:CLASSIFICATION -->\n    29\t```\n    30\t\n    31\t**Classification decision tree** (`.claude/commands/sc/task-unified.md`, `src/superclaude/core/ORCHESTRATOR.md:152`):\n    32\t1. Check `--compliance` override → use it at 100% confidence\n    33\t2. Detect compound phrases (e.g., `\"quick fix\"` → LIGHT; `\"fix security\"` → STRICT) → apply with +0.15 boost\n    34\t3. Score all keywords by tier weight (STRICT +0.4, EXEMPT +0.4, LIGHT +0.3, STANDARD +0.2)\n    35\t4. Apply context boosters (>2 files +0.3 STRICT; security paths +0.4 STRICT; docs paths +0.5 EXEMPT)\n    36\t5. Resolve conflicts: priority STRICT > EXEMPT > LIGHT > STANDARD\n    37\t6. If confidence < 0.70, prompt user for confirmation\n...\n    52\t\n    53\t**Verification routing by tier** (`src/superclaude/skills/sc-tasklist-protocol/rules/tier-classification.md:76`):\n    54\t- STRICT → quality-engineer sub-agent (3–5K token budget, 60s timeout)\n    55\t- STANDARD → direct test execution (300–500 tokens, 30s timeout)\n    56\t- LIGHT → quick sanity check (~100 tokens, 10s)\n    57\t- EXEMPT → no verification (0 tokens, 0s)\n    58\t\n    59\t**Critical path override**: Paths matching `auth/`, `security/`, `crypto/`, `models/`, `migrations/` always trigger CRITICAL verification regardless of compliance tier — a path-based safety override that cannot be suppressed by keyword classification.\n...\n\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.5RigorFlowMerger/improvement-backlog.md\n...\n   175\t\n   176\t**Priority**: P0\n   177\t**Effort**: S\n   178\t**Component**: Task-Unified Tier System\n   179\t**Classification**: strengthen existing code\n   180\t\n   181\t**Change description**:\n   182\tA `CriticalFailCondition` dataclass shall be added. `GateCriteria` shall add a `critical_conditions: list[CriticalFailCondition]` field with default empty list. When any critical condition is matched, `gate_passed()` shall return `(False, f\"CRITICAL: {condition_type}\")` unconditionally. The sc-task-unified-protocol SKILL.md shall document three named CRITICAL conditions for STRICT-tier tasks.\n...\n\nPath: tests/sc-roadmap/unit/test_template_discovery.py\n     1\t\"\"\"\n     2\tUnit tests for Wave 2 template discovery hierarchy (T3.1).\n     3\t\n     4\tTests the template discovery process defined in SKILL.md:\n     5\t- 4-level search order (local → user → plugin → inline)\n     6\t- Template matching criteria\n     7\t- Fallback to inline generation\n     8\t- Template scoring\n     9\t\"\"\"\n    10\t\n    11\timport os\n    12\timport re\n    13\t\n    14\timport pytest\n    15\t\n    16\t\n    17\t# Template search paths from SKILL.md\n    18\tTEMPLATE_SEARCH_ORDER = [\n    19\t    (\"./templates/roadmaps/\", 1, \"Local project templates\"),\n    20\t    (\"~/.claude/templates/roadmaps/\", 2, \"User templates\"),\n    21\t    (\"plugins/superclaude/templates/roadmaps/\", 3, \"Plugin templates\"),\n    22\t    (\"inline\", 4, \"Generated variant (fallback)\"),\n    23\t]\n...\n\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.0_fidelity-refactor_/wiring-verification-gate-v1.0-release-spec.md\n     1\t---\n     2\trelease: wiring-verification-gate-v1.0\n     3\tversion: 1.0.0\n     4\tstatus: draft\n     5\tdate: 2026-03-17\n     6\tparent_analysis: cli-portify-executor-noop-forensic-report.md\n     7\tparent_ranking: proposal-ranking.md\n     8\tfidelity_link: \"Link 3: Tasklist -> Code\"\n     9\tpriority: P0\n    10\testimated_scope: 300-400 lines production code\n    11\t---\n    12\t\n    13\t# Wiring Verification Gate v1.0 -- Release Specification\n    14\t\n    15\t## 1. Problem Statement\n...\n    39\t\n    40\t1. Detect unwired injectable dependencies (`Optional[Callable] = None` never provided at any call site)\n    41\t2. Detect orphan modules (exported functions never imported by any consumer)\n    42\t3. Detect unwired dispatch registries (dictionary entries mapping to non-importable functions)\n    43\t4. Emit a structured YAML report compatible with the `GateCriteria`/`SemanticCheck` pattern\n    44\t5. Deploy in shadow mode initially, with a path to soft and full enforcement\n    45\t\n    46\t### Non-Goals (v1.0)\n...\n   387\t```\n   388\t\n   389\t### 4.3 Report Format\n   390\t\n   391\tThe wiring analysis emits a Markdown file with YAML frontmatter, conforming to\n   392\tthe `GateCriteria` validation pattern used by all existing gates.\n   393\t\n   394\t```markdown\n   395\t---\n   396\tgate: wiring-verification\n   397\ttarget_dir: src/superclaude/cli/cli_portify\n   398\tfiles_analyzed: 14\n   399\tunwired_count: 1\n   400\torphan_count: 2\n   401\tregistry_count: 0\n   402\ttotal_findings: 3\n   403\tanalysis_complete: true\n   404\tenforcement_mode: shadow\n   405\t---\n   406\t\n   407\t# Wiring Verification Report\n   408\t\n   409\t## Unwired Callables (1)\n   410\t\n   411\t### WF-001: PortifyExecutor.step_runner\n...\n   689\t\n   690\t| Field | Type | Constraint |\n   691\t|-------|------|-----------|\n   692\t| `gate` | string | Must be `\"wiring-verification\"` |\n   693\t| `target_dir` | string | Non-empty |\n   694\t| `files_analyzed` | int | >= 0 |\n   695\t| `unwired_count` | int | Must be 0 for gate pass |\n   696\t| `orphan_count` | int | Must be 0 for gate pass |\n   697\t| `registry_count` | int | Must be 0 for gate pass |\n   698\t| `total_findings` | int | Must equal sum of above three |\n   699\t| `analysis_complete` | bool | Must be true |\n   700\t| `whitelist_entries_applied` | int | >= 0; count of whitelist entries that suppressed findings |\n   701\t\n   702\t---\n   703\t\n   704\t## 7. Risk Assessment\n...\n   867\t\n   868\t| SC | Description | Verification |\n   869\t|----|-------------|-------------|\n   870\t| SC-001 | Wiring gate detects `Optional[Callable] = None` never provided at call site | Unit test: `test_detect_unwired_callable_basic` |\n   871\t| SC-002 | Wiring gate detects orphan modules in `steps/` directories | Unit test: `test_detect_orphan_module` |\n   872\t| SC-003 | Wiring gate detects unresolvable registry entries | Unit test: `test_detect_unwired_registry` |\n   873\t| SC-004 | Report conforms to `GateCriteria` validation pattern | Unit test: `test_gate_passes_clean_report` |\n   874\t| SC-005 | `gate_passed()` evaluates `WIRING_GATE` without modification | Integration test: `test_cli_portify_fixture` |\n...\n\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/anti-instincts-gate-unified.md\n...\n   110\t\n   111\tA deterministic, regex-based post-generation pass that scans the merged roadmap for scaffolding terms and verifies each has a corresponding discharge task in a later phase. Catches the failure mode where early phases use \"mocked\", \"stub\", \"skeleton\", \"placeholder\" language that creates implicit obligations that later phases never fulfill.\n   112\t\n   113\t### Detection Axis\n   114\t\n   115\tV2-A's obligation scanner detects a fundamentally different failure mode than omission-based approaches. Rather than checking whether a requirement is present, it checks whether deferred commitments are fulfilled. This catches bugs where the requirement IS mentioned (as scaffolding) but the follow-through is missing.\n   116\t\n   117\t### Implementation\n...\n   947\t\n   948\t### Enforcement Strategy\n   949\t\n   950\t<!-- Source: V1-C (spec structural audit), adapted per refactor-plan -->\n   951\t\n   952\tPhase 1 (immediate): Warning-only. The executor logs a warning if the ratio falls below 0.5 but does not block the pipeline. This allows shadow-mode validation on real specs before enforcement.\n   953\t\n   954\tPhase 2 (after validation): STRICT enforcement. If the structural count suggests the extraction is missing significant content, the executor re-triggers extraction or halts with an actionable error.\n   955\t\n   956\t---\n   957\t\n   958\t## 8. Gate Definition\n   959\t\n   960\t<!-- Source: Merge (new content bridging V2+V5) -->\n   961\t\n   962\t### New Gate: `ANTI_INSTINCT_GATE`\n   963\t\n   964\t**File**: `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/gates.py` (modify existing)\n   965\t\n   966\t```python\n   967\t# --- Anti-Instinct Gate check functions ---\n...\n  1069\t```\n  1070\t\n  1071\t### Why a Separate Gate\n  1072\t\n  1073\t<!-- Source: Merge (new content bridging V2+V5) -->\n  1074\t\n  1075\tThe `MERGE_GATE` validates the merge step's output quality (heading hierarchy, cross-refs, duplicates). The anti-instinct checks validate cross-artifact semantic fidelity -- a different concern. Keeping them separate follows the existing pattern where each gate corresponds to one validation concern. The `MERGE_GATE` runs on the merged roadmap; the `ANTI_INSTINCT_GATE` runs on the anti-instinct audit report produced by the executor.\n  1076\t\n  1077\t### Anti-Instinct Audit Report Format\n  1078\t\n  1079\tThe executor produces `output_dir / \"anti-instinct-audit.md\"` with frontmatter:\n...\n  1395\t\n  1396\t| File | Changes | Source |\n  1397\t|---|---|---|\n  1398\t| `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/gates.py` | Add `ANTI_INSTINCT_GATE` definition with 3 semantic checks; add 3 check functions (`_no_undischarged_obligations`, `_integration_contracts_covered`, `_fingerprint_coverage_check`); update `ALL_GATES` list to insert `(\"anti-instinct\", ANTI_INSTINCT_GATE)` between `merge` and `test-strategy` | V2-A + V5-1 + V4-2 |\n  1399\t| `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/executor.py` | Add anti-instinct step to `_build_steps()`; add structural audit hook after extract (`_run_structural_audit`); add `_run_anti_instinct_audit()` function; add import for `ANTI_INSTINCT_GATE`; update `_get_all_step_ids()` to include `\"anti-instinct\"` | All |\n...\n\nPath: docs/generated/sprint-tui-v2-requirements.md\n...\n