{"parentUuid":"93cf1403-a308-4ccc-8298-9eded77d63bc","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"c427fd48-a12c-49c9-b76a-efbd6120eac3","agentId":"af29f71b461c23f95","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_tlg3bdXrzQoD8wUSJkCj9iBn","type":"tool_result","content":"   958→## 8. Gate Definition\n   959→\n   960→<!-- Source: Merge (new content bridging V2+V5) -->\n   961→\n   962→### New Gate: `ANTI_INSTINCT_GATE`\n   963→\n   964→**File**: `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/gates.py` (modify existing)\n   965→\n   966→```python\n   967→# --- Anti-Instinct Gate check functions ---\n   968→\n   969→def _no_undischarged_obligations(content: str) -> bool:\n   970→    \"\"\"Verify all scaffolding obligations in early phases are discharged by later phases.\n   971→\n   972→    Runs V2-A obligation scanner on the anti-instinct audit report content.\n   973→    The actual scan has already been performed by the executor; this check\n   974→    validates the frontmatter result.\n   975→    \"\"\"\n   976→    fm = _parse_frontmatter(content)\n   977→    if fm is None:\n   978→        return False\n   979→    try:\n   980→        return int(fm.get(\"undischarged_obligations\", -1)) == 0\n   981→    except (ValueError, TypeError):\n   982→        return False\n   983→\n   984→\n   985→def _integration_contracts_covered(content: str) -> bool:\n   986→    \"\"\"Verify all integration contracts from spec are covered in roadmap.\n   987→\n   988→    This check requires both spec and roadmap content. Since semantic\n   989→    checks receive only a single content string, the real enforcement\n   990→    happens in the executor. This validates the executor's written result.\n   991→    \"\"\"\n   992→    fm = _parse_frontmatter(content)\n   993→    if fm is None:\n   994→        return False\n   995→    try:\n   996→        return int(fm.get(\"uncovered_contracts\", -1)) == 0\n   997→    except (ValueError, TypeError):\n   998→        return False\n   999→\n  1000→\n  1001→def _fingerprint_coverage_check(content: str) -> bool:\n  1002→    \"\"\"Verify spec code-level identifiers have sufficient roadmap coverage.\n  1003→\n  1004→    This check requires both spec and roadmap content. Since semantic\n  1005→    checks receive only a single content string, the real enforcement\n  1006→    happens in the executor. This validates the executor's written result.\n  1007→    \"\"\"\n  1008→    fm = _parse_frontmatter(content)\n  1009→    if fm is None:\n  1010→        return False\n  1011→    try:\n  1012→        return float(fm.get(\"fingerprint_coverage\", 0.0)) >= 0.7\n  1013→    except (ValueError, TypeError):\n  1014→        return False\n  1015→\n  1016→\n  1017→# --- Gate definition ---\n  1018→\n  1019→ANTI_INSTINCT_GATE = GateCriteria(\n  1020→    required_frontmatter_fields=[\n  1021→        \"undischarged_obligations\",    # V2-A: integer count\n  1022→        \"uncovered_contracts\",         # V5-1: integer count\n  1023→        \"fingerprint_coverage\",        # V4-2: float 0.0-1.0\n  1024→    ],\n  1025→    min_lines=10,\n  1026→    enforcement_tier=\"STRICT\",\n  1027→    semantic_checks=[\n  1028→        SemanticCheck(\n  1029→            name=\"no_undischarged_obligations\",\n  1030→            check_fn=_no_undischarged_obligations,\n  1031→            failure_message=(\n  1032→                \"Undischarged scaffolding obligations detected: early-phase \"\n  1033→                \"mocks/stubs/skeletons have no corresponding replace/integrate/\"\n  1034→                \"wire task in later phases\"\n  1035→            ),\n  1036→        ),\n  1037→        SemanticCheck(\n  1038→            name=\"integration_contracts_covered\",\n  1039→            check_fn=_integration_contracts_covered,\n  1040→            failure_message=(\n  1041→                \"Spec integration contracts missing from roadmap: dispatch tables, \"\n  1042→                \"registries, or injection points defined in spec have no explicit \"\n  1043→                \"wiring task in roadmap\"\n  1044→            ),\n  1045→        ),\n  1046→        SemanticCheck(\n  1047→            name=\"fingerprint_coverage_sufficient\",\n  1048→            check_fn=_fingerprint_coverage_check,\n  1049→            failure_message=(\n  1050→                \"Spec code-level identifiers missing from roadmap: fingerprint \"\n  1051→                \"coverage ratio below 0.7 threshold\"\n  1052→            ),\n  1053→        ),\n  1054→    ],\n  1055→)\n  1056→```\n  1057→\n  1058→### Position in ALL_GATES\n  1059→\n  1060→```python\n  1061→ALL_GATES = [\n  1062→    ...\n  1063→    (\"merge\", MERGE_GATE),\n  1064→    (\"anti-instinct\", ANTI_INSTINCT_GATE),   # NEW\n  1065→    (\"test-strategy\", TEST_STRATEGY_GATE),\n  1066→    (\"spec-fidelity\", SPEC_FIDELITY_GATE),\n  1067→    ...\n  1068→]\n  1069→```\n  1070→\n  1071→### Why a Separate Gate\n  1072→\n  1073→<!-- Source: Merge (new content bridging V2+V5) -->\n  1074→\n  1075→The `MERGE_GATE` validates the merge step's output quality (heading hierarchy, cross-refs, duplicates). The anti-instinct checks validate cross-artifact semantic fidelity -- a different concern. Keeping them separate follows the existing pattern where each gate corresponds to one validation concern. The `MERGE_GATE` runs on the merged roadmap; the `ANTI_INSTINCT_GATE` runs on the anti-instinct audit report produced by the executor.\n  1076→\n  1077→### Anti-Instinct Audit Report Format\n  1078→\n  1079→The executor produces `output_dir / \"anti-instinct-audit.md\"` with frontmatter:\n  1080→\n  1081→```yaml\n  1082→---\n  1083→undischarged_obligations: 0\n  1084→uncovered_contracts: 0\n  1085→fingerprint_coverage: 0.85\n  1086→total_obligations: 3\n  1087→discharged_obligations: 3\n  1088→total_contracts: 2\n  1089→covered_contracts: 2\n  1090→total_fingerprints: 15\n  1091→matched_fingerprints: 13\n  1092→structural_audit_passed: true\n  1093→---\n  1094→```\n  1095→\n  1096→This file is the gate artifact. The `ANTI_INSTINCT_GATE` validates its frontmatter fields. The executor writes it after running all three deterministic checks.\n  1097→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"uuid":"8e389ca2-a41e-4ecf-bf67-c1b305cb7c76","timestamp":"2026-03-17T18:49:46.128Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"93cf1403-a308-4ccc-8298-9eded77d63bc","userType":"external","cwd":"/config/workspace/IronClaude","sessionId":"caf57f20-b6f0-47d7-a404-b3840c9c44e5","version":"2.1.77","gitBranch":"v3.0-AuditGates","slug":"bright-juggling-reef"}
